text=Oh, the @@remind@@ program, how I love and loathe thee. Remind is a program that is used to remind you of appointments, holidays, and the like, and can be used to generate appointment calendars. It's a farily nifty program, but the syntax is rather horrendous.%0a%0a!! Obtaining and installing remind%0aYou can obtain remind from http://www.roaringpenguin.com/products/remind, who now supports it. Installation is simple, it's very self-contained.%0a%0a!! Ecosystem%0a%0a:There's a remind mailing list at: http://lists.roaringpenguin.com/cgi-bin/mailman/listinfo/remind-fans%0a:There is also a remind wiki at: http://www.roaringpenguin.com/wiki/index.php/Remind%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a!! Using remind%0aRemind reads a @@.rem@@ file, alternatively, it can read a directory of @@.rem@@ files. The command line is basically:%0a%0a[@%0a  remind [OPTIONS] filename [date] [*rep] [time]%0a@]%0a%0a''filename'' can either be a single file, or a directory, of which only the files ending in @@.rem@@ will be read.%0a%0aThings like birthdays and holidays are very simple to do in remind:%0a%0a[@%0a  REM 13 December MSG Dad's Birthday!%0a@]%0a%0aRemind has this somewhat annoying feature that every message it spits out has an extra line feed. To avoid this, place a percent (%25) sign at the end of the message:%0a%0a[@%0a  REM 13 December MSG Dad's Birthday! %25%0a@]%0a%0a!!! Something a little more advanced:%0a%0a[@%0a  REM 13 SATISFY [wkdaynum($T) == 5] MSG Happy Triskaidekaphilia Day!%25%0a@]%0a%0a@@SATISFY@@ is used to determine whether to fire the reminder based on some characteristics other than the actual trigger date. The above only fires when the 13th falls on a Friday (weekday number 5).%0a%0a!! Collections of remind files%0a%0aI have been keeping a collection of remind files as a git repository at https://gitorious.org/nix-utilities/remind-files which includes at least one file you really want to have: @@00-defs.rem@@ as this sets up several useful and interesting definitions that can be used in your reminder recipes.%0a%0a%0a!! Making your .rem files available everywhere%0a%0aI work on several different computers and portable devices. The simplest way to keep all these computers in sync with the same remind files is to use something like [[Dropbox -> http://dropbox.com]] and putting your .rem files in a directory in your @@~/Dropbox@@ directory. They you just point the @@remind@@ command at that directory:%0a%0a[@%0a  remind [options] ~/Dropbox/Reminders%0a@]%0a%0aand Bob's your Uncle.%0a%0a%0a>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:An event reminder tool for Linux%0aParent:(Technology.)Tools%0aincludeme:[[(Technology.)Tools]]%0aCategories:[[!Articles]]%0aTags: reminders, calendars, hard landscape%0a(:tags-hide reminders, calendars, hard landscape :)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a
