diff:1348103730:1342979054:=46a47,88%0a> !! Recipe: marking special weeks%0a> At least in the US, we seem to designate somethings as "National X Month" or "National X Week". The first is really easy:%0a> %0a> [@%0a>   REM July MSG July is National Blueberry Month%0a> @]%0a> %0a> (real holiday)%0a> %0a> But making a week-long event is a little harder. You basically have to test if the trigger date is between the bounds of a given week. Luckily, this is easy to set into a function:%0a> %0a> [@%0a>   FSET All_Week_1(x)	day(x) %3c=  7%0a>   FSET All_Week_2(x)	day(x) >=  8 && day(x) %3c= 15%0a>   FSET All_Week_3(x)	day(x) >= 16 && day(x) %3c= 22%0a>   FSET All_Week_4(x)	day(x) >= 23 && day(x) %3c= 29%0a>   FSET All_Week_5(x)	day(x) >= 30%0a> @]%0a> %0a> Then, in your recipe, you simply put:%0a> %0a> [@%0a>   REM month SATISFY [All_Week_1($T)] MSG First week of %25m is %25_ \%0a>      events%0a> @]%0a> %0a> Where month becomes the month name, e.g. July, Aug, etc.%0a> %0a> The above shows something else as well. The ''%25m'' variable gives the current month in the output. The ''%25_'' variable causes a new line. This is kind of nice to do something like:%0a> %0a> [@%0a>   REM Jan MSG The month of January is: %25_ \%0a>     National Bath Safety Month %25_ \%0a>     National Blood Donor Month %25_ \%0a>     National Braille Literacy Month %25_ \%0a>     National Hobby Month %25_ \%0a>     Hot Tea Month %25_ \%0a>     National Oatmeal Month %25_ \%0a>     National Soup Month%0a> @]%0a> %0a> Which prints out all those designations indented under the first message line.%0a
