diff:1342975827:1342975827:=1,73d0%0a%3c Oh, the @@remind@@ program, how I love and loathe thee. Remind is a program that is used to remind you of appointments, holidays, and the like, and can be used to generate appointment calendars. It's a farily nifty program, but the syntax is rather horrendous.%0a%3c %0a%3c !! Obtaining and installing remind%0a%3c You can obtain remind from http://www.roaringpenguin.com, who now supports it. Installation is simple, it's very self-contained.%0a%3c %0a%3c !! Using remind%0a%3c Remind reads a @@.rem@@ file, alternatively, it can read a directory of @@.rem@@ files. The command line is basically:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   remind [OPTIONS] filename [date] [*rep] [time]%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c ''filename'' can either be a single file, or a directory, of which only the files ending in @@.rem@@ will be read.%0a%3c %0a%3c Things like birthdays and holidays are very simple to do in remind:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   REM 13 December MSG Dad's Birthday!%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c Remind has this somewhat annoying feature that every message it spits out has an extra line feed. To avoid this, place a percent (%25) sign at the end of the message:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   REM 13 December MSG Dad's Birthday! %25%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c !! Collections of remind files%0a%3c %0a%3c I have been keeping a collection of remind files as a git repository at https://gitorious.org/nix-utilities/remind-files which includes at least one file you really want to have: @@00-defs.rem@@ as this sets up several useful and interesting definitions that can be used in your reminder recipes.%0a%3c %0a%3c !! Recipe: marking special weeks%0a%3c At least in the US, we seem to designate somethings as "National X Month" or "National X Week". The first is really easy:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   REM July MSG July is National Blueberry Month%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c (real holiday)%0a%3c %0a%3c But making a week-long event is a little harder. You basically have to test if the trigger date is between the bounds of a given week. Luckily, this is easy to set into a function:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   FSET All_Week_1(x)	day(x) %3c=  7%0a%3c   FSET All_Week_2(x)	day(x) >=  8 && day(x) %3c= 15%0a%3c   FSET All_Week_3(x)	day(x) >= 16 && day(x) %3c= 22%0a%3c   FSET All_Week_4(x)	day(x) >= 23 && day(x) %3c= 29%0a%3c   FSET All_Week_5(x)	day(x) >= 30%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c Then, in your recipe, you simply put:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   REM month SATISFY [All_Week_1($T)] MSG First week of %25m is %25_ \%0a%3c      events%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c Where month becomes the month name, e.g. July, Aug, etc.%0a%3c %0a%3c The above shows something else as well. The ''%25m'' variable gives the current month in the output. The ''%25_'' variable causes a new line. This is kind of nice to do something like:%0a%3c %0a%3c [@%0a%3c   REM Jan MSG The month of January is: %25_ \%0a%3c     National Bath Safety Month %25_ \%0a%3c     National Blood Donor Month %25_ \%0a%3c     National Braille Literacy Month %25_ \%0a%3c     National Hobby Month %25_ \%0a%3c     Hot Tea Month %25_ \%0a%3c     National Oatmeal Month %25_ \%0a%3c     National Soup Month%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a%3c Which prints out all those designations indented under the first message line.%0a%3c %0a
